Yes, you are absolutely correct. The bug is located in the **SpatialHashGrid** class, specifically within the `insert` method.

### The Logic Error
In your `SpatialHashGrid.insert` method, you are creating a **new object literal** `{ mesh, box }` inside the nested loops for every grid cell the object occupies.

```javascript
// Current implementation in your code
insert(mesh, box) {
    // ... loops through x and z ...
    for (let x = minX; x <= maxX; x++) {
        for (let z = minZ; z <= maxZ; z++) {
            const key = `${x}:${z}`;
            if (!this.cells.has(key)) {
                this.cells.set(key, []);
            }
            // ERROR: A new object reference is created here for every cell!
            this.cells.get(key).push({ mesh, box }); 
        }
    }
}
```

### Why this causes the "Momentum Bug"
When the player moves, the `physicsStep` calls `spatialGrid.query(playerBox)`.
1.  **Deduplication Failure:** The `query` method uses a JavaScript `Set` to deduplicate results (`results.add(item)`). `Set` relies on object reference identity. Because you created *different* wrapper objects for the *same* mesh in every cell, the `Set` sees them as unique items.
2.  **Redundant Checks:** If the floor mesh spans multiple cells (which it does), `query` returns the **same floor mesh multiple times** (e.g., 2, 4, or more times depending on the player's position).
3.  **Physics Instability:** Your collision loop then runs collision resolution logic on the Floor multiple times in a single frame. While collision logic should ideally be idempotent (repeatable without side effects), running it repeatedly can cause floating-point rounding errors or performance spikes. A performance spike results in a larger `dt` (delta time) for the next frame, causing the player to sink deeper into the floor than intended. If they sink deeper than `0.1` units, your "wall detection" logic (`overlapY > 0.1`) triggers, falsely identifying the floor as a wall and setting `velocity.x` and `velocity.z` to `0`, instantly stopping the player.

### The Fix (For Future Reference)
To fix this, you would simply create the wrapper object **once** before entering the loops, so every cell stores a reference to the same object. The `Set` in `query` will then correctly filter out duplicates.

```javascript
insert(mesh, box) {
    // ... calculate min/max ...

    // Create the item ONCE
    const item = { mesh, box }; 

    for (let x = minX; x <= maxX; x++) {
        for (let z = minZ; z <= maxZ; z++) {
            const key = `${x}:${z}`;
            if (!this.cells.has(key)) this.cells.set(key, []);

            // Push the SAME reference
            this.cells.get(key).push(item); 
        }
    }
}

